  "body": "### Component\n\nForge\n\n### Describe the feature you would like\n\nWhen I omit the `http://` prefix for a url with `forge test --fork-url localhost:8545`, I see the following error:\r\n```bash\r\nThe application panicked (crashed).\r\nMessage:  could not instantiate forked environment: \r\nFailed to get latest block number\r\n\r\nContext:\r\n- Error #0: builder error for url (localhost:8545): URL scheme is not allowed\r\n- Error #1: URL scheme is not allowed\r\nLocation: evm/src/executor/opts.rs:68\r\n```\r\n\r\nWhen I use `--fork-url http://localhost:8545`, there is no error. I observe similar behavior when omitting `http://` prefix with `--rpc-url` as well.\r\n\r\nThe error message is already pretty good! Just seems like omitting the prefix could be a common mistake (or it's just me?), and forge doesn't explicitly say that it wants an `http://` prefix. I propose either (a) making a special case to allow for non-prefixed localhost, or (b) change the error message to something like the following.\r\n```bash\r\n- Error #0: builder error for url (localhost:8545): non-prefixed URL scheme is not allowed\r\n- Error $1: non-prefixed URL scheme is not allowed\r\n```\n\n### Additional context\n\n_No response_",
